ales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1270–1335":"1270–1335","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1296–Female":"1296–Deceased","1299–1323":"1299–1323","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1305":"1305","ABT 1296":"about 1296","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","ABT 1300":"about 1300","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1270":"1270","Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Wales","of Dinorwig, Llanddeiniolen, Caernarvon, Wales":"Dinorwic, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llanddeiniolen, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Llanddeiniolen, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Rees  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Rice  .","German: habitational name from a place in the Rhineland called Rees.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Andreas  ."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]},{"name":"Llwyd","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Same as Lhuyd, q v."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Gruffudd Llwyd ap Rhys was born in 1270, in Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom. He married Gwenllian ferch Cynan in 1297, in Caernarfonshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 6 daughters. He died in 1335, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1270–1335":"1270–1335","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1296–Female":"1296–Surnud","1299